<subsection xml:id="subsec-trigonometry-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Trigonometry in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Trigonometry 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Reflect on the use of trigonometry in real-life situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction xml:id="intro-trig-real-life">
        <p>
            Trigonometric ratios are powerful tools used to find unknown angles or side lengths in right-angled triangles. 
            These ratios have many real-life applications in fields such as architecture, engineering, navigation, 
            sports, surveying, and construction.
        </p>
        <p>
            In this section, you will explore how sine, cosine, and tangent are used to solve practical problems 
            involving heights, distances, and angles in everyday situations.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <!-- ACTIVITY -->
    <activity xml:id="activity-trig-real-life-design">
        <title>Designing a Kite</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <em>Work in pairs or small groups.</em>
            </p>
            <p>
                In this activity, you will design a kite and use trigonometry to calculate 
                the lengths of the pieces needed to build it.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <term>What you need:</term>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Paper, pencil, and ruler</p></li>
                        <li><p>A protractor</p></li>
                        <li><p>Calculator</p></li>
                        <li><p>(Optional) Sticks, string, and paper/plastic for building</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A traditional kite is made from two sticks crossing at right angles. 
                    The vertical stick (spine) is <m>60\,\text{cm}</m> long. The horizontal stick (spar) 
                    crosses the spine <m>15\,\text{cm}</m> from the top.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Draw a labelled diagram of this kite shape, marking the lengths given.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If the top edge of the kite (from the top of the spine to the end of the spar) 
                    makes an angle of <m>60^\circ</m> with the spine, use trigonometry to calculate 
                    the length of half the spar (from center to tip).
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Calculate the length of the top edge of the kite (the string from the top 
                    of the spine to the end of the spar). Give your answer in exact form.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The bottom section of the kite has its edge making an angle of <m>30^\circ</m> with the spine. 
                    Calculate the length of the bottom edge of the kite in exact form.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the total length of string needed to go around the outside of the kite.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <term>Extension:</term> If you have materials, build your kite! 
                    Compare your calculated measurements with the actual lengths you cut.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>

    <!-- EXAMPLES SECTION -->

    <example xml:id="ex-tree-shadow">
        <title>Finding the Height of an Acacia Tree</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A farmer in Kajiado County wants to estimate the height of an acacia tree in her field. 
                On a sunny afternoon, the tree casts a shadow that is <m>12\,\text{m}</m> long. 
                If the angle of elevation of the sun is <m>45^\circ</m>, find the height of the tree.
            </p>
            <image width="55%">
            <latex-image label="ex-tree-shadow-diag">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Ground line (savanna)
                    \draw[very thick, yellow!70!brown] (-1,0) -- (8,0);
                    % Shadow (on ground)
                    \draw[very thick, gray!50, fill=gray!20] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5,0.1) -- (0,0.1) -- cycle;
                    \node[below] at (2.5,-0.2) {Shadow = $12\,\text{m}$};
                    % Acacia tree trunk
                    \draw[very thick, brown, fill=brown!60] (4.9,0) -- (5.1,0) -- (5.1,4.8) -- (4.9,4.8) -- cycle;
                    % Acacia flat-top canopy (umbrella shape)
                    \draw[very thick, green!50!black, fill=green!40] (3,3.8) -- (5,4.5) -- (7,3.8) -- (6.5,3.5) -- (5,4) -- (3.5,3.5) -- cycle;
                    \draw[very thick, green!50!black, fill=green!50] (3.5,4) -- (5,4.8) -- (6.5,4) -- (6,3.8) -- (5,4.3) -- (4,3.8) -- cycle;
                    % Height label
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick] (7.2,0) -- (7.2,4.8);
                    \node[right] at (7.3,2.4) {$h = ?$};
                    % Sun ray
                    \draw[very thick, orange, dashed] (0,0) -- (5,5);
                    % Angle of elevation
                    \draw (1,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=45, radius=1cm];
                    \node at (1.5,0.4) {$45^\circ$};
                    % Right angle
                    \draw (4.7,0) -- (4.7,0.3) -- (5,0.3);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                In this right triangle:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p>The shadow (adjacent side) = <m>12\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>The angle of elevation = <m>45^\circ</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>The height <m>h</m> is the opposite side</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using tangent:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\tan\,45^\circ \amp= \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{h}{12}</mrow>
                    <mrow>h \amp= 12 \times \tan\,45^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= 12 \times 1</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= 12\,\text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The height of the acacia tree is <m>12\,\text{m}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <em>Note:</em> This result makes sense because when the angle of elevation is <m>45^\circ</m>, 
                the height equals the shadow length since <m>\tan\,45^\circ = 1</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-football-goal">
        <title>Angle of a Football Shot</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A football player stands <m>18\,\text{m}</m> away from the goal. 
                The crossbar of the goal is <m>2.4\,\text{m}</m> high. At what angle of elevation 
                must the player kick the ball so that it just clears the crossbar?
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
            <latex-image label="ex-football-goal-diag">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Ground/pitch
                    \draw[very thick, green!70!black] (-0.5,0) -- (7.5,0);
                    % Goal posts
                    \draw[very thick, white, fill=white] (6.8,0) rectangle (7,2.4);
                    \draw[very thick, white, fill=white] (6,0) rectangle (6.2,2.4);
                    \draw[very thick, white, fill=white] (6,2.3) rectangle (7,2.5);
                    % Net (simplified)
                    \draw[gray, thin] (6.1,0.3) -- (7.3,0.3);
                    \draw[gray, thin] (6.1,0.6) -- (7.3,0.6);
                    \draw[gray, thin] (6.1,0.9) -- (7.3,0.9);
                    \draw[gray, thin] (6.1,1.2) -- (7.3,1.2);
                    \draw[gray, thin] (6.1,1.5) -- (7.3,1.5);
                    \draw[gray, thin] (6.1,1.8) -- (7.3,1.8);
                    \draw[gray, thin] (6.1,2.1) -- (7.3,2.1);
                    % Ball trajectory
                    \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (0,0) -- (6.5,2.4);
                    % Ball
                    \draw[fill=white, thick] (0,0) circle (0.15);
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) ++(45:0.15) -- ++(45:-0.3);
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) ++(135:0.15) -- ++(135:-0.3);
                    % Player (simplified stick figure)
                    \draw[thick] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,0.8);
                    \draw[thick, fill=cyan] (-0.5,0.9) circle (0.12);
                    \draw[thick] (-0.5,0.5) -- (-0.8,0.2);
                    \draw[thick] (-0.5,0.5) -- (-0.2,0.2);
                    \draw[thick] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.7,-0.3);
                    \draw[thick] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.3,-0.3);
                    % Angle
                    \draw (0.8,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=20, radius=0.8cm];
                    \node at (1.3,0.25) {$\theta$};
                    % Distance label
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick] (0,-0.5) -- (6.5,-0.5);
                    \node[below] at (3.25,-0.5) {$18\,\text{m}$};
                    % Height label
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick] (7.4,0) -- (7.4,2.4);
                    \node[right] at (7.5,1.2) {$2.4\,\text{m}$};
                    % Right angle
                    \draw (6.5,0) -- (6.5,0.25) -- (6.75,0.25);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                In this right triangle:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p>The horizontal distance (adjacent) = <m>18\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>The height of crossbar (opposite) = <m>2.4\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>We need to find the angle <m>\theta</m></p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using tangent:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp= \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{2.4}{18}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp= 0.1333</mrow>
                    <mrow>\theta \amp= \tan^{-1}(0.1333)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\theta \amp= 7.6^\circ</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The player must kick the ball at an angle of elevation of at least <m>7.6^\circ</m> 
                to clear the crossbar.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-kite-flying-2">
        <title>Flying a Kite</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A child is flying a kite with a string that is <m>50\,\text{m}</m> long. 
                If the string makes an angle of <m>60^\circ</m> with the ground, find the exact height of the kite 
                above the child's hand. (Assume the string is taut and straight.)
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="ex-kite-flying-diag">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Ground line
                    \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (5,0);
                    % Child
                    \draw[thick] (0.5,0) -- (0.5,1);
                    \draw[thick, fill=cyan] (0.5,1.1) circle (0.12);
                    \draw[thick] (0.5,0.7) -- (0.2,0.4);
                    \draw[thick] (0.5,0.7) -- (0.9,1.3);
                    \draw[thick] (0.5,0) -- (0.3,-0.3);
                    \draw[thick] (0.5,0) -- (0.7,-0.3);
                    % String
                    \draw[very thick, brown] (0.9,1.3) -- (3.5,5.5);
                    % Kite
                    \draw[thick, fill=red!70] (3.5,5.5) -- (3.8,5.2) -- (3.5,4.5) -- (3.2,5.2) -- cycle;
                    \draw[thick, blue] (3.5,4.5) -- (3.5,3.8);
                    \draw[thick, blue] (3.5,4.5) -- (3.3,3.9);
                    \draw[thick, blue] (3.5,4.5) -- (3.7,3.9);
                    % Height dashed line
                    \draw[dashed, thick] (3.5,1.3) -- (3.5,5.5);
                    % Horizontal dashed line
                    \draw[dashed, thick] (0.9,1.3) -- (3.5,1.3);
                    % Angle
                    \draw (1.5,1.3) arc[start angle=0, end angle=60, radius=0.6cm];
                    \node at (1.9,1.7) {$60^\circ$};
                    % Labels
                    \node[left, rotate=60] at (2,3.5) {$50\,\text{m}$};
                    \node[right] at (3.6,3.4) {$h = ?$};
                    % Right angle
                    \draw (3.2,1.3) -- (3.2,1.6) -- (3.5,1.6);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                In this right triangle:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p>The string (hypotenuse) = <m>50\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>The angle with the horizontal = <m>60^\circ</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>The height <m>h</m> is the opposite side</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using sine:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\sin\,60^\circ \amp= \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{h}{50}</mrow>
                    <mrow>h \amp= 50 \times \sin\,60^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= 50 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= 25\sqrt{3}\,\text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The kite is exactly <m>25\sqrt{3}\,\text{m}</m> above the child's hand, which is approximately <m>43.3\,\text{m}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-rhombus-diagonals">
        <title>Diagonals of a Rhombus Tile</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A craftsman in Lamu is creating decorative floor tiles in the shape of rhombuses. 
                Each rhombus has sides of length <m>10\,\text{cm}</m> and one interior angle of <m>60^\circ</m>. 
                Find the lengths of both diagonals of the rhombus.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="ex-rhombus-diagonals-diag">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Rhombus
                    \draw[very thick, fill=orange!30] (0,0) -- (3,1.732) -- (6,0) -- (3,-1.732) -- cycle;
                    % Diagonals
                    \draw[thick, blue, dashed] (0,0) -- (6,0);
                    \draw[thick, red, dashed] (3,1.732) -- (3,-1.732);
                    % Center point
                    \fill (3,0) circle (0.08);
                    % Angle marks
                    \draw (0.6,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=30, radius=0.6cm];
                    \draw (0.6,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=-30, radius=0.6cm];
                    \node at (1.1,0.35) {$30^\circ$};
                    \node at (1.1,-0.35) {$30^\circ$};
                    % Right angle at center
                    \draw (3,0.25) -- (3.25,0.25) -- (3.25,0);
                    % Side length
                    \node[above, rotate=30] at (1.3,1) {$10\,\text{cm}$};
                    % Diagonal labels
                    \node[below, blue] at (3,-0.2) {$d_1$};
                    \node[right, red] at (3.2,0.9) {$d_2$};
                    % Angle label at vertex
                    \node at (0.3,0) {$60^\circ$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The diagonals of a rhombus bisect each other at right angles and also bisect the interior angles.
            </p>
            <p>
                At the <m>60^\circ</m> vertex, each half-angle is <m>30^\circ</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Using the right triangle formed by half of each diagonal and one side:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Half of longer diagonal: } \quad \frac{d_1}{2} \amp= 10 \times \cos\,30^\circ = 10 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = 5\sqrt{3}\,\text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\therefore d_1 \amp= 10\sqrt{3} \approx 17.32\,\text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Half of shorter diagonal: } \quad \frac{d_2}{2} \amp= 10 \times \sin\,30^\circ = 10 \times \frac{1}{2} = 5\,\text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\therefore d_2 \amp= 10\,\text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The diagonals are <m>10\sqrt{3} \approx 17.32\,\text{cm}</m> and <m>10\,\text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-roof-pitch">
        <title>Constructing a Mabati Roof</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A family in Machakos is building a house with a mabati (iron sheet) roof that makes an angle of <m>30^\circ</m> with the horizontal.
                If the width of the house is <m>10\,\text{m}</m>, and the roof is symmetric, 
                find the exact length of one side of the roof (from the edge to the peak).
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
            <latex-image label="ex-roof-pitch-diag">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % House walls
                    \draw[very thick, brown, fill=brown!20] (0,0) rectangle (6,2.5);
                    % Windows
                    \draw[thick, fill=cyan!30] (0.8,1) rectangle (1.8,2);
                    \draw[thick] (1.3,1) -- (1.3,2);
                    \draw[thick] (0.8,1.5) -- (1.8,1.5);
                    \draw[thick, fill=cyan!30] (4.2,1) rectangle (5.2,2);
                    \draw[thick] (4.7,1) -- (4.7,2);
                    \draw[thick] (4.2,1.5) -- (5.2,1.5);
                    % Door
                    \draw[thick, fill=brown!60] (2.5,0) rectangle (3.5,1.8);
                    \draw[fill=yellow] (3.3,0.9) circle (0.08);
                    % Roof
                    \draw[very thick, red!70!black, fill=red!40] (0,2.5) -- (3,4.23) -- (6,2.5) -- cycle;
                    % Roof side length
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick, blue] (-0.3,2.5) -- (2.7,4.23);
                    \node[left, blue, rotate=30] at (0.8,3.5) {$L = ?$};
                    % Angle
                    \draw (0.8,2.5) arc[start angle=0, end angle=30, radius=0.8cm];
                    \node at (1.4,2.75) {$30^\circ$};
                    % Width label
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;, thick] (0,-0.4) -- (6,-0.4);
                    \node[below] at (3,-0.4) {$10\,\text{m}$};
                    % Half-width
                    \draw[dashed] (3,2.5) -- (3,4.23);
                    \node[below] at (1.5,2.4) {$5\,\text{m}$};
                    % Right angle
                    \draw (2.7,2.5) -- (2.7,2.8) -- (3,2.8);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since the roof is symmetric, each half-span is <m>\frac{10}{2} = 5\,\text{m}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                In the right triangle formed by half the roof:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p>The half-width (adjacent) = <m>5\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>The roof angle = <m>30^\circ</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>The roof length <m>L</m> is the hypotenuse</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using cosine:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\cos\,30^\circ \amp= \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{5}{L}</mrow>
                    <mrow>L \amp= \frac{5}{\cos\,30^\circ}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{5}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{10}{\sqrt{3}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{10\sqrt{3}}{3}\,\text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Each side of the mabati roof is exactly <m>\frac{10\sqrt{3}}{3}\,\text{m}</m>, which is approximately <m>5.77\,\text{m}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-hexagon-beehive">
        <title>Dimensions of a Hexagonal Beehive Frame</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A beekeeper in Baringo is building frames for beehives. Each frame has a regular hexagonal shape 
                with sides of length <m>6\,\text{cm}</m>. Using trigonometry, find the exact values of:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li><p>The distance from the center of the hexagon to any corner.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The distance from the center to the middle of any side.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The total width of the hexagon (measured across two opposite corners).</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <image width="45%">
            <latex-image label="ex-hexagon-beehive-diag">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Regular hexagon
                    \draw[very thick, fill=yellow!30] (0:2) -- (60:2) -- (120:2) -- (180:2) -- (240:2) -- (300:2) -- cycle;
                    % Center point
                    \fill (0,0) circle (0.08);
                    \node[below left] at (0,0) {O};
                    % Radius to vertex
                    \draw[thick, blue] (0,0) -- (60:2);
                    \node[above left, blue] at (0.5,1) {$r$};
                    % Line to midpoint
                    \draw[thick, red] (0,0) -- (30:1.732);
                    \node[red] at (0.8,0.7) {$h$};
                    % Side label
                    \node[above] at (90:2.1) {$6\,\text{cm}$};
                    % Central angle
                    \draw (0.5,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=60, radius=0.5cm];
                    \node at (0.8,0.15) {$60^\circ$};
                    % Right angle at midpoint
                    \draw[rotate=30] (1.5,0) -- (1.5,0.2) -- (1.732,0.2);
                    % Vertex labels
                    \node[right] at (0:2.15) {A};
                    \node[above right] at (60:2.15) {B};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                A regular hexagon can be divided into 6 equilateral triangles. The angle at the center for each triangle is <m>\frac{360^\circ}{6} = 60^\circ</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <em>a) Distance from center to corner:</em>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since each triangle is equilateral, the distance from the center to any corner equals the side length:
                <me>r = 6\,\text{cm}</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <em>b) Distance from center to middle of a side:</em>
            </p>
            <p>
                Drawing a line from the center to the middle of a side creates a right angle. 
                This line, half a side, and the line to the corner form a right triangle with a <m>30^\circ</m> angle at the center.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>h \amp= r \times \cos\,30^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= 6 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= 3\sqrt{3}\,\text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The distance from the center to the middle of any side is exactly <m>3\sqrt{3}\,\text{cm}</m>, 
                which is approximately <m>5.20\,\text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <em>c) Width across opposite corners:</em>
            </p>
            <p>
                The width across opposite corners is twice the distance from center to corner:
                <me>\text{Width} = 2r = 2 \times 6 = 12\,\text{cm}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

