        <exercise xml:id="ex-parallelogram-land">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A farmer in Nyandarua owns a piece of land in the shape of a parallelogram. 
                    The longer sides measure <m>120\,\text{m}</m> and the perpendicular distance between them is <m>40\sqrt{3}\,\text{m}</m>. 
                    If one interior angle is <m>60^\circ</m>, find the total length of fencing needed to enclose the land.
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-parallelogram-land">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Parallelogram
                        \draw[very thick, fill=green!20] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (6.5,2.6) -- (1.5,2.6) -- cycle;
                        % Angle
                        \draw (0.7,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=60, radius=0.7cm];
                        \node at (1.1,0.4) {$60^\circ$};
                        % Side labels
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {$120\,\text{m}$};
                        % Height (perpendicular distance)
                        \draw[dashed, thick] (1.5,0) -- (1.5,2.6);
                        \draw (1.5,0.3) -- (1.2,0.3) -- (1.2,0);
                        \node[right] at (1.55,1.3) {$40\sqrt{3}\,\text{m}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    First, find the length of the shorter sides using trigonometry. 
                    Let <m>s</m> be the length of a shorter side.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using sine: <m>\sin\,60^\circ = \frac{40\sqrt{3}}{s}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>s = \frac{40\sqrt{3}}{\sin\,60^\circ} = \frac{40\sqrt{3}}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}} = 40\sqrt{3} \times \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} = 80\,\text{m}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The perimeter of the parallelogram is:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter = <m>2 \times 120 + 2 \times 80 = 240 + 160 = 400\,\text{m}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The farmer needs <m>400\,\text{m}</m> of fencing to enclose the land.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

